SKILL|hermes-agent|"Configure, extend, or contribute to Hermes Agent."
STEP|1|**Self-improving through skills** — Hermes learns from experience by saving reusable procedures as skills. When it solves a complex problem, discovers a workflow, or gets corrected, it can persist tha
STEP|2|**Persistent memory across sessions** — remembers who you are, your preferences, environment details, and lessons learned. Pluggable memory backends (built-in, Honcho, Mem0, and more) let you choose h
STEP|3|**Multi-platform gateway** — the same agent runs on Telegram, Discord, Slack, WhatsApp, Signal, Matrix, Email, and 10+ other platforms with full tool access, not just chat.
STEP|4|**Provider-agnostic** — swap models and providers mid-workflow without changing anything else. Credential pools rotate across multiple API keys automatically.
STEP|5|**Profiles** — run multiple independent Hermes instances with isolated configs, sessions, skills, and memory.
STEP|6|**Extensible** — plugins, MCP servers, custom tools, webhook triggers, cron scheduling, and the full Python ecosystem.
STEP|7|This skill helps you work with Hermes Agent effectively** — setting it up, configuring features, spawning additional agent instances, troubleshooting issues, finding the right commands and settings, a
STEP|8|Docs:** https://hermes-agent.nousresearch.com/docs/
STEP|9|+ providers supported. Set via `hermes model` or `hermes setup`.
STEP|10|Restart required.** `security.redact_secrets` is snapshotted at import time — toggling it mid-session (e.g. via `export HERMES_REDACT_SECRETS=false` from a tool call) will NOT take effect for the runn
STEP|11|`manual` — always prompt (default)
STEP|12|`smart` — use an auxiliary LLM to auto-approve low-risk commands, prompt on high-risk
STEP|13|`off` — skip all approval prompts (equivalent to `--yolo`)
STEP|14|`hermes --yolo …`
STEP|15|`export HERMES_YOLO_MODE=1`
STEP|16|**Local faster-whisper** — free, no API key: `pip install faster-whisper`
STEP|17|**Groq Whisper** — free tier: set `GROQ_API_KEY`
STEP|18|**OpenAI Whisper** — paid: set `VOICE_TOOLS_OPENAI_KEY`
STEP|19|**Mistral Voxtral** — set `MISTRAL_API_KEY`
STEP|20|**Prefer `delegate_task` for quick subtasks** — less overhead than spawning a full process
STEP|21|**Use `-w` (worktree mode)** when spawning agents that edit code — prevents git conflicts
STEP|22|**Set timeouts** for one-shot mode — complex tasks can take 5-10 minutes
STEP|23|**Use `hermes chat -q` for fire-and-forget** — no PTY needed
STEP|24|**Use tmux for interactive sessions** — raw PTY mode has `\r` vs `\n` issues with prompt_toolkit
STEP|25|**For scheduled tasks**, use the `cronjob` tool instead of spawning — handles delivery and retry
STEP|26|**Single:** `delegate_task(goal, context, toolsets)`.
STEP|27|**Batch:** `delegate_task(tasks=[{goal, ...}, ...])` runs children in
STEP|28|**Roles:** `leaf` (default; cannot re-delegate) vs `orchestrator`
STEP|29|**Not durable.** If the parent is interrupted, the child is
STEP|30|**Schedules:** duration (`"30m"`, `"2h"`), "every" phrase
STEP|31|**Per-job knobs:** `skills`, `model`/`provider` override, `script`
STEP|32|**Invariants:** 3-minute hard interrupt per run, `.tick.lock` file
STEP|33|**CLI:** `hermes curator <verb>` — `status`, `run`, `pause`, `resume`,
STEP|34|**Slash:** `/curator <subcommand>` mirrors the CLI.
STEP|35|**Scope:** only touches skills with `created_by: "agent"` provenance.
STEP|36|**Telemetry:** sidecar at `~/.hermes/skills/.usage.json` holds
STEP|37|**CLI verbs (common):** `init`, `create`, `list` (alias `ls`),
STEP|38|**Worker/orchestrator toolset:** `kanban_show`, `kanban_complete`,
STEP|39|**Dispatcher** runs inside the gateway by default
STEP|40|**Isolation:** board is the hard boundary (workers get
STEP|41|Alt+Enter doesn't insert a newline.** Windows Terminal intercepts Alt+Enter
STEP|42|Diagnosing keybindings.** Run `python scripts/keystroke_diagnostic.py`
STEP|43|HTTP 400 "No models provided" on first run.** `config.yaml` was saved
STEP|44|WinError 10106** ("The requested service provider could not be loaded
STEP|45|`scripts/run_tests.sh` doesn't work as-is on Windows** — it looks for
STEP|46|user site, then invoke pytest directly with `PYTHONPATH` set:
STEP|47|POSIX-only tests need skip guards.** Common markers already in the codebase:
STEP|48|Symlinks — elevated privileges on Windows
STEP|49|`0o600` file modes — POSIX mode bits not enforced on NTFS by default
STEP|50|`signal.SIGALRM` — Unix-only (see `tests/conftest.py::_enforce_test_timeout`)
STEP|51|Winsock / Windows-specific regressions — `@pytest.mark.skipif(sys.platform != "win32", ...)`
STEP|52|Line endings.** Git may warn `LF will be replaced by CRLF the next time
STEP|53|Forward slashes work almost everywhere.** `C:/Users/...` is accepted by
STEP|54|Check `stt.enabled: true` in config.yaml
STEP|55|Verify provider: `pip install faster-whisper` or set API key
STEP|56|In gateway: `/restart`. In CLI: exit and relaunch.
STEP|57|`hermes tools` — check if toolset is enabled for your platform
STEP|58|Some tools need env vars (check `.env`)
STEP|59|`/reset` after enabling tools
STEP|60|`hermes doctor` — check config and dependencies
STEP|61|`hermes auth` — re-authenticate OAuth providers (or `hermes auth add <provider>`)
STEP|62|Check `.env` has the right API key
STEP|63|**Copilot 403**: `gh auth login` tokens do NOT work for Copilot API. You must use the Copilot-specific OAuth device code flow via `hermes model` → GitHub Copilot.
STEP|64|**Tools/skills:** `/reset` starts a new session with updated toolset
STEP|65|**Config changes:** In gateway: `/restart`. In CLI: exit and relaunch.
STEP|66|**Code changes:** Restart the CLI or gateway process
STEP|67|`hermes skills list` — verify installed
STEP|68|`hermes skills config` — check platform enablement
STEP|69|Load explicitly: `/skill name` or `hermes -s name`
STEP|70|**Gateway dies on SSH logout**: Enable linger: `sudo loginctl enable-linger $USER`
STEP|71|**Gateway dies on WSL2 close**: WSL2 requires `systemd=true` in `/etc/wsl.conf` for systemd services to work. Without it, gateway falls back to `nohup` (dies when session closes).
STEP|72|**Gateway crash loop**: Reset the failed state: `systemctl --user reset-failed hermes-gateway`
STEP|73|**Discord bot silent**: Must enable **Message Content Intent** in Bot → Privileged Gateway Intents.
STEP|74|**Slack bot only works in DMs**: Must subscribe to `message.channels` event. Without it, the bot ignores public channels.
STEP|75|**Windows-specific issues** (`Alt+Enter` newline, WinError 10106, UTF-8 BOM config, test suite, line endings): see the dedicated **Windows-Specific Quirks** section above.
STEP|76|Create `tools/your_tool.py`:**
STEP|77|Add to `toolsets.py`** → `_HERMES_CORE_TOOLS` list.
STEP|78|Add `CommandDef` to `COMMAND_REGISTRY` in `hermes_cli/commands.py`
STEP|79|Add handler in `cli.py` → `process_command()`
STEP|80|(Optional) Add gateway handler in `gateway/run.py`
STEP|81|Tests auto-redirect `HERMES_HOME` to temp dirs — never touch real `~/.hermes/`
STEP|82|Run full suite before pushing any change
STEP|83|Use `-o 'addopts='` to clear any baked-in pytest flags
STEP|84|Windows contributors:** `scripts/run_tests.sh` currently looks for POSIX venvs (`.venv/bin/activate` / `venv/bin/activate`) and will error out on Windows where the layout is `venv/Scripts/activate` + 
STEP|85|Cross-platform test guards:** tests that use POSIX-only syscalls need a skip marker. Common ones already in the codebase:
STEP|86|Symlink creation → `@pytest.mark.skipif(sys.platform == "win32", reason="Symlinks require elevated privileges on Windows")` (see `tests/cron/test_cron_script.py`)
STEP|87|POSIX file modes (0o600, etc.) → `@pytest.mark.skipif(sys.platform.startswith("win"), reason="POSIX mode bits not enforced on Windows")` (see `tests/hermes_cli/test_auth_toctou_file_modes.py`)
STEP|88|`signal.SIGALRM` → Unix-only (see `tests/conftest.py::_enforce_test_timeout`)
STEP|89|Live Winsock / Windows-specific regression tests → `@pytest.mark.skipif(sys.platform != "win32", reason="Windows-specific regression")`
STEP|90|Monkeypatching `sys.platform` is not enough** when the code under test also calls `platform.system()` / `platform.release()` / `platform.mac_ver()`. Those functions re-read the real OS independently, 
STEP|91|**Local terminal backend** → emit host info (OS, `$HOME`, cwd) + Windows-specific notes (hostname ≠ username, `terminal` uses bash not PowerShell).
STEP|92|**Remote terminal backend** (anything in `_REMOTE_TERMINAL_BACKENDS`: `docker, singularity, modal, daytona, ssh, managed_modal`) → **suppress** host info entirely and describe only the backend. A live
STEP|93|**Key fact for prompt authoring:** when `TERMINAL_ENV != "local"`, *every* file tool (`read_file`, `write_file`, `patch`, `search_files`) runs inside the backend container, not on the host. The system
STEP|94|Refactor-safety pattern (POSIX-equivalence guard):** when you extract inline logic into a helper that adds Windows/platform-specific behavior, keep a `_legacy_<name>` oracle function in the test file 
STEP|95|**Never break prompt caching** — don't change context, tools, or system prompt mid-conversation
STEP|96|**Message role alternation** — never two assistant or two user messages in a row
STEP|97|Use `get_hermes_home()` from `hermes_constants` for all paths (profile-safe)
STEP|98|Config values go in `config.yaml`, secrets go in `.env`
STEP|99|New tools need a `check_fn` so they only appear when requirements are met
